1
00:00:01,125 --> 00:00:03,828
[dynamic music]

2
00:00:13,805 --> 00:00:16,407
[gentle music]

3
00:00:35,293 --> 00:00:37,996
[birds singing]

4
00:01:00,618 --> 00:01:03,221
[music continues]

5
00:01:17,702 --> 00:01:20,405
[birds singing]

6
00:01:35,420 --> 00:01:38,723
[music continues]

7
00:02:06,250 --> 00:02:07,285
Yes?

8
00:02:07,618 --> 00:02:09,420
They've started in the conference room.

9
00:02:09,720 --> 00:02:10,755
[woman] Okay, good.

10
00:02:14,725 --> 00:02:17,462
I need you to pull up a couple of files for me today.

11
00:02:19,330 --> 00:02:20,665
I need 'em before lunch.

12
00:02:21,099 --> 00:02:23,267
Need State v. Wilkins .

13
00:02:23,801 --> 00:02:26,070
The other one is probably in the advance files...

14
00:02:26,737 --> 00:02:28,106
I like your attack,

15
00:02:28,239 --> 00:02:30,308
but now if you want them to believe your version

16
00:02:30,441 --> 00:02:32,777
of the events, you have to make them see it.

17
00:02:32,910 --> 00:02:33,945
- You have to-- - Clara?

18
00:02:34,078 --> 00:02:35,079
- Sir? - You have call.

19
00:02:35,513 --> 00:02:36,547
Just a second.

20
00:02:37,048 --> 00:02:38,483
[clears throat] It's the professor.

21
00:02:39,250 --> 00:02:40,384
Tell him I'll call him right back.

22
00:02:40,885 --> 00:02:41,919
It's about your mother.

23
00:02:44,889 --> 00:02:47,024
[gentle music]

24
00:02:47,692 --> 00:02:48,726
Excuse me.

25
00:02:53,364 --> 00:02:55,133
The earliest memory I have is the sound

26
00:02:55,266 --> 00:02:57,101
of my mother's voice.

27
00:02:58,436 --> 00:02:59,937
Though I was too young to understand

28
00:03:00,071 --> 00:03:03,641
the meaning of her words, I do remember the feeling.

29
00:03:04,976 --> 00:03:07,044
The feeling of being drawn to her voice,

30
00:03:07,178 --> 00:03:08,713
like a moth to the moon.

31
00:03:09,847 --> 00:03:11,249
When I was finally able to understand

32
00:03:11,382 --> 00:03:12,416
what she was saying,

33
00:03:12,550 --> 00:03:14,385
the feeling only grew stronger.

34
00:03:16,487 --> 00:03:18,990
You see, my mother was a storyteller.

35
00:03:20,158 --> 00:03:22,326
Some say, the best Savannah had ever known.

36
00:03:23,861 --> 00:03:25,763
Oh, people would come from miles around

37
00:03:25,930 --> 00:03:28,666
to hear her weave a tale about the low country,

38
00:03:28,799 --> 00:03:31,369
and not once did they ever leave disappointed.

39
00:03:34,205 --> 00:03:36,007
As I grew older, however,

40
00:03:36,874 --> 00:03:38,910
the fascination with my mother's stories

41
00:03:39,043 --> 00:03:40,077
began to fade.

42
00:03:42,813 --> 00:03:45,683
I found myself longing for more than

43
00:03:45,816 --> 00:03:48,719
the hot, languid days of South Georgia.

44
00:03:51,522 --> 00:03:54,859
At the age of 17, I finally left the magical,

45
00:03:54,992 --> 00:03:57,628
mysterious Savannah of my childhood.

46
00:03:58,829 --> 00:04:04,802
And until the day my mother died, Savannah left me.

47
00:04:11,709 --> 00:04:13,878
[indistinct chattering]

48
00:04:21,953 --> 00:04:23,955
- Hey, Aunt Clara! - Oh, Jamie,

49
00:04:24,088 --> 00:04:25,723
look, you're losing your teeth!

50
00:04:25,856 --> 00:04:28,593
- Hi, baby. - [dog barking]

51
00:04:29,493 --> 00:04:31,262
And you remember Alexa, Philomena's little girl?

52
00:04:31,395 --> 00:04:34,065
Yes, I do, her big girl, hi darling.

53
00:04:34,198 --> 00:04:36,133
Hi. I'm sorry about your mom.

54
00:04:36,334 --> 00:04:37,935
- I liked her a lot. - Thank you.

55
00:04:38,069 --> 00:04:41,606
Hmm. I knew there was a lawyer in the house.

56
00:04:41,739 --> 00:04:43,441
My skin was starting to crawl.

57
00:04:43,574 --> 00:04:45,943
Well, now, hush! This is no time for jokes.

58
00:04:46,077 --> 00:04:47,445
Leave him alone, Wallis.

59
00:04:47,578 --> 00:04:49,847
Doctors always think they're so funny.

60
00:04:49,981 --> 00:04:51,649
You still practicing medicine?

61
00:04:52,783 --> 00:04:53,951
[Professor] Good Lord,

62
00:04:54,085 --> 00:04:56,120
what the hell did you do to your hair?

63
00:04:56,254 --> 00:04:57,822
It's called style, Professor.

64
00:04:57,955 --> 00:05:00,124
I doubt if you've ever heard the word.

65
00:05:00,791 --> 00:05:02,693
You look beautiful, honey. It's good to see you.

66
00:05:02,827 --> 00:05:05,162
Okay, everybody, back to the table.

67
00:05:05,296 --> 00:05:06,330
We gotta finish our dinner.

68
00:05:06,464 --> 00:05:07,598
[Jamie] But I don't like the peas.

69
00:05:07,732 --> 00:05:09,133
Well, I don't mind if you don't like peas,

70
00:05:09,267 --> 00:05:10,701
you just have to eat five.

71
00:05:10,835 --> 00:05:13,170
- If you don't eat five-- - When did the number

72
00:05:13,304 --> 00:05:14,772
- go down? - [Wallis] Oh no,

73
00:05:14,905 --> 00:05:16,340
the number went up!

74
00:05:16,474 --> 00:05:19,510
[indistinct chattering]

75
00:05:27,084 --> 00:05:30,988
[mysterious music]

76
00:05:35,426 --> 00:05:37,828
[owl hooting]

77
00:05:39,597 --> 00:05:41,165
[water splashing]

78
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:44,802
[water splashing]

79
00:05:58,482 --> 00:06:00,985
[tense music]

80
00:06:07,625 --> 00:06:09,694
[water splashing]

81
00:06:18,469 --> 00:06:19,737
[dog barking]

82
00:06:19,870 --> 00:06:21,505
Kids, now hush, hush, hush.

83
00:06:21,639 --> 00:06:24,909
You are gonna wake Clara up, shh, quiet!

84
00:06:25,042 --> 00:06:26,243
[whispers] You have to keep quiet.

85
00:06:26,377 --> 00:06:29,647
Well, I think the key today is to keep her busy.

86
00:06:29,980 --> 00:06:31,048
Mm.

87
00:06:31,215 --> 00:06:32,950
You know, so she doesn't think too much.

88
00:06:33,484 --> 00:06:35,786
Would that be the key to your success, Philomena?

89
00:06:35,920 --> 00:06:36,921
[Wallis] Daddy.

90
00:06:37,621 --> 00:06:39,090
Very funny, Professor.

91
00:06:40,057 --> 00:06:42,593
Oh, Wallis,

92
00:06:43,728 --> 00:06:46,697
maybe you and I should take her to the club for lunch.

93
00:06:47,365 --> 00:06:49,767
Well, now I believe

94
00:06:49,900 --> 00:06:52,136
that is among the worst ideas I ever heard.

95
00:06:52,370 --> 00:06:54,338
What? I think that'd be nice.

96
00:06:54,505 --> 00:06:56,407
What, you think surrounding a grieving woman

97
00:06:56,540 --> 00:06:59,710
with a lot of nosy, drunken housewives is nice?

98
00:06:59,844 --> 00:07:01,979
Well, maybe you're right.

99
00:07:02,713 --> 00:07:05,149
I have to go see the minister about the service, so,

100
00:07:06,250 --> 00:07:09,153
why don't you two take Clara for a nice walk in woods, hm?

101
00:07:09,387 --> 00:07:11,522
I can't think of anything more dreadful.

102
00:07:12,223 --> 00:07:14,058
I'd love to take a walk in the woods.

103
00:07:14,191 --> 00:07:15,259
If it's not a bother.

104
00:07:16,394 --> 00:07:17,428
Oh, Clara.

105
00:07:18,295 --> 00:07:19,597
Honey.

106
00:07:19,864 --> 00:07:22,133
I am so sorry about your mama.

107
00:07:24,402 --> 00:07:27,605
Now, if there is anything I can do, anything at all.

108
00:07:27,738 --> 00:07:29,073
How about a cup of coffee?

109
00:07:30,074 --> 00:07:31,175
Certainly.

110
00:07:31,909 --> 00:07:33,411
- Morning. - Morning.

111
00:07:35,679 --> 00:07:38,149
You really wanna come for a walk with us?

112
00:07:38,749 --> 00:07:39,817
Yeah, I do.

113
00:07:40,384 --> 00:07:42,353
- You really wanna take me? - Yeah.

114
00:07:42,720 --> 00:07:43,921
Okay.

115
00:07:44,121 --> 00:07:46,457
[Alexa] We know where your name's carved in a tree.

116
00:07:51,162 --> 00:07:52,930
This is where we put ours.

117
00:07:55,399 --> 00:07:56,434
[clears throat]

118
00:07:57,168 --> 00:08:03,908
Jamie plus Alexa, the year 2000, best friends forever.

119
00:08:04,742 --> 00:08:05,943
Well, look at that.

120
00:08:06,877 --> 00:08:08,612
Yours is on the other side.

121
00:08:12,483 --> 00:08:16,287
"Wallis plus Clara, 1970.

122
00:08:17,321 --> 00:08:18,989
Best friends forever."

123
00:08:20,724 --> 00:08:22,827
They call this the friendship tree.

124
00:08:23,027 --> 00:08:24,161
Yeah.

125
00:08:24,295 --> 00:08:26,297
That's what my mom told us.

126
00:08:30,601 --> 00:08:31,635
[Jamie] Whoa!

127
00:08:34,271 --> 00:08:36,073
Sometimes he shows up.

128
00:08:36,474 --> 00:08:37,975
Sometimes he doesn't.

129
00:08:39,677 --> 00:08:41,178
What's his name again?

130
00:08:41,312 --> 00:08:43,714
Fish Man. Half fish, half man.

131
00:08:45,049 --> 00:08:46,484
Did your mother ever tell you about the man

132
00:08:46,617 --> 00:08:47,818
who lived out in the woods?

133
00:08:48,352 --> 00:08:50,888
- [Jamie] Nope. - My mother told us about him.

134
00:08:52,356 --> 00:08:55,259
She said, "If you ever got lost in the woods,

135
00:08:55,392 --> 00:08:58,095
you shouldn't worry, because there's a man who lived

136
00:08:58,229 --> 00:09:00,164
out in the woods who would come and get you

137
00:09:00,297 --> 00:09:01,499
and bring you back home."

138
00:09:02,533 --> 00:09:06,203
And we spent hours and hours trying to get ourselves lost.

139
00:09:07,037 --> 00:09:08,739
And finally I said to my mother, I said,

140
00:09:08,873 --> 00:09:12,243
"Mama, there ain't no man that lives out in the woods."

141
00:09:12,710 --> 00:09:16,013
And she just smiled and said, "Oh yes there is,

142
00:09:16,146 --> 00:09:18,249
you just lucky you haven't needed him."

143
00:09:18,782 --> 00:09:20,851
You mean, you never saw him?

144
00:09:22,086 --> 00:09:23,921
Nope, never did.

145
00:09:24,188 --> 00:09:25,456
[bell tolling]

146
00:09:25,623 --> 00:09:27,291
[bird cawing]

147
00:09:27,424 --> 00:09:31,228
35 years ago, Mattie Collier showed up at my door

148
00:09:31,362 --> 00:09:36,267
with a baby in her arms and asked me for a job.

149
00:09:36,667 --> 00:09:38,569
Well, I didn't really have much to offer,

150
00:09:40,170 --> 00:09:41,572
but she seemed like a nice woman.

151
00:09:41,705 --> 00:09:44,241
So I said to her, "How's your cooking?"

152
00:09:45,175 --> 00:09:46,210
Well.

153
00:09:47,745 --> 00:09:51,115
She gave me her brightest smile and said,

154
00:09:51,248 --> 00:09:55,052
"I guarantee you've never tasted anything like it."

155
00:09:55,819 --> 00:09:58,122
[people laugh]

156
00:09:59,590 --> 00:10:00,724
[Professor] She was right.

157
00:10:02,693 --> 00:10:05,896
Turns out Mattie was one of the worst cooks

158
00:10:06,030 --> 00:10:08,732
to ever step foot into the low country.

159
00:10:09,233 --> 00:10:11,235
[people laugh]

160
00:10:11,368 --> 00:10:12,903
[Professor] I didn't know what to do.

161
00:10:14,939 --> 00:10:18,342
But then, about a week later,

162
00:10:19,443 --> 00:10:22,212
and maybe 10 pounds lighter,

163
00:10:23,948 --> 00:10:27,918
I overheard her telling a bedtime story to the kids.

164
00:10:29,920 --> 00:10:35,926
As I listened from the hallway, she lured me into a world

165
00:10:36,293 --> 00:10:37,928
I didn't even know existed.

166
00:10:38,062 --> 00:10:41,832
A world so full of magic and wonder,

167
00:10:41,966 --> 00:10:43,834
that by the end I wanted to pack my bags

168
00:10:43,968 --> 00:10:45,169
and go there myself.

169
00:10:47,805 --> 00:10:50,507
I knew right then that Mattie Collier

170
00:10:51,575 --> 00:10:53,310
had a gift from God.

171
00:10:54,311 --> 00:10:56,714
I took her right downstairs that evening,

172
00:10:57,815 --> 00:11:01,952
and I said, "Mattie, I cannot let you cook another meal

173
00:11:02,086 --> 00:11:05,122
in this house, but I'll tell you what.

174
00:11:06,890 --> 00:11:08,359
I'll pay you twice what you're getting now

175
00:11:08,492 --> 00:11:10,461
if you'll stay and tell stories."

176
00:11:12,429 --> 00:11:14,665
And she looked at me like I was crazy and said,

177
00:11:14,798 --> 00:11:16,734
"Tell stories to who?"

178
00:11:17,701 --> 00:11:21,038
"To whomever will listen," I answered.

179
00:11:21,972 --> 00:11:23,540
With God as my witness,

180
00:11:25,809 --> 00:11:27,811
money could not have been better spent.

181
00:11:31,015 --> 00:11:32,116
I'm gonna miss Mattie.

182
00:11:32,449 --> 00:11:33,651
[clears throat]

183
00:11:35,686 --> 00:11:40,591
But I believe we should all take comfort from the knowledge

184
00:11:40,724 --> 00:11:45,362
that her spirit remains in every story she ever told.

185
00:11:46,964 --> 00:11:52,970
Stories that will be told again, and again, and again.

186
00:11:57,574 --> 00:11:59,710
May she grace heaven as she did the Earth.

187
00:12:01,545 --> 00:12:05,049
Clara, honey, I want you to meet some neighbors of ours,

188
00:12:05,182 --> 00:12:07,017
this is Marianne and Alfred Brooks.

189
00:12:07,384 --> 00:12:08,552
Oh yes, hello.

190
00:12:08,686 --> 00:12:10,154
- Hi. - My mother told me

191
00:12:10,287 --> 00:12:11,488
all about you.

192
00:12:11,622 --> 00:12:14,224
As matter of fact, I have one of your photographs

193
00:12:14,358 --> 00:12:15,726
on my office wall.

194
00:12:15,859 --> 00:12:17,061
That's right.

195
00:12:17,194 --> 00:12:18,862
That beautiful old tree.

196
00:12:18,996 --> 00:12:20,264
What'd your mama call it?

197
00:12:20,664 --> 00:12:21,865
The wishing tree.

198
00:12:22,199 --> 00:12:23,734
What's the wishing tree?

199
00:12:23,867 --> 00:12:25,069
[Marianne] The wishing tree, my dear,

200
00:12:25,202 --> 00:12:28,272
is a magical tree from one of Mattie's stories.

201
00:12:28,706 --> 00:12:30,374
I never heard about it.

202
00:12:30,507 --> 00:12:32,276
Mattie told you that story at your birthday party.

203
00:12:32,409 --> 00:12:33,911
- Don't you remember? - [Jamie] Did not.

204
00:12:34,044 --> 00:12:35,746
- Oh, she did! - [all laugh]

205
00:12:35,879 --> 00:12:36,914
No.

206
00:12:37,047 --> 00:12:38,782
Do you know the story, Clara?

207
00:12:38,949 --> 00:12:41,819
Um, I'm afraid I don't remember that one.

208
00:12:42,553 --> 00:12:43,587
I do.

209
00:12:44,922 --> 00:12:48,192
Will you tell it to us, Grandpa? Please?

210
00:12:48,325 --> 00:12:49,893
- [Alexa] Please? Pretty please. - [Jamie] Please.

211
00:12:50,394 --> 00:12:51,829
Oh, come on Daddy, tell us.

212
00:12:52,029 --> 00:12:53,597
[chuckles]

213
00:12:58,335 --> 00:13:01,638
The wishing tree is a very old story.

214
00:13:01,939 --> 00:13:06,076
Took place way back in 1851

215
00:13:06,777 --> 00:13:09,847
on a dark and scary August night.

216
00:13:11,949 --> 00:13:13,217
It was on that night,

217
00:13:13,717 --> 00:13:16,253
a little slave girl named Celia

218
00:13:16,386 --> 00:13:19,456
tried to escape from a plantation down the road.

219
00:13:21,058 --> 00:13:24,762
Unfortunately, she didn't get very far

220
00:13:24,895 --> 00:13:26,663
before the storm came.

221
00:13:26,797 --> 00:13:29,466
And what a storm it was!

222
00:13:29,600 --> 00:13:33,170
Thunder so loud, it made the trees shake.

223
00:13:33,370 --> 00:13:34,605
- Boom! - [thunder rumbles]

224
00:13:34,738 --> 00:13:35,773
[chuckles]

225
00:13:35,906 --> 00:13:38,475
- [dramatic music] - [thunder cracking]

226
00:13:38,609 --> 00:13:41,111
[horse neighing]

227
00:13:42,079 --> 00:13:45,149
[men shouting indistinctly]

228
00:13:46,483 --> 00:13:48,051
Come back here, girl!

229
00:13:52,689 --> 00:13:56,260
- [dogs barking] - [men shouting]

230
00:13:56,560 --> 00:13:58,462
Right this way, boys, she's down this way!

231
00:14:00,264 --> 00:14:02,366
[music continues]

232
00:14:02,499 --> 00:14:05,369
[men shouting]

233
00:14:13,477 --> 00:14:15,546
[dogs barking]

234
00:14:16,446 --> 00:14:19,683
[thunder cracking]

235
00:14:25,189 --> 00:14:26,623
[man] That's it, right here, right here.

236
00:14:29,693 --> 00:14:30,894
We got her, we got her!

237
00:14:32,262 --> 00:14:34,898
Please, please don't let them get me!

238
00:14:35,165 --> 00:14:37,201
- [thunder cracking] - [horse neighing]

239
00:14:37,334 --> 00:14:38,368
[man] Celia!

240
00:14:39,169 --> 00:14:41,205
[music continues]

241
00:14:42,005 --> 00:14:43,173
Come on out of there, girl.

242
00:14:43,607 --> 00:14:45,309
I'm gonna have to shoot you down.

243
00:14:46,977 --> 00:14:48,212
I mean it, now!

244
00:14:48,612 --> 00:14:49,847
[gun firing]

245
00:14:50,147 --> 00:14:52,616
You're gonna be dead before you're free, girl.

246
00:14:52,749 --> 00:14:55,252
[gun firing repeatedly]

247
00:14:56,086 --> 00:14:59,556
[Professor] He could have shot at that tree all night,

248
00:14:59,690 --> 00:15:02,593
but it wouldn't have made a bit of difference.

249
00:15:04,328 --> 00:15:08,131
You see, Celia was gone!

250
00:15:09,499 --> 00:15:10,601
Disappeared!

251
00:15:12,569 --> 00:15:17,441
Next morning, she awoke next to an elm tree in Philadelphia.

252
00:15:17,574 --> 00:15:22,112
Had no idea where she was or how she got there.

253
00:15:23,747 --> 00:15:27,351
But of one thing she was absolutely certain,

254
00:15:28,585 --> 00:15:32,322
for the first time in her life, she was free.

255
00:15:32,756 --> 00:15:33,991
[chuckles]

256
00:15:34,124 --> 00:15:36,593
All because of the wishing tree.

257
00:15:36,860 --> 00:15:38,695
[all chuckle]

258
00:15:38,862 --> 00:15:41,098
- [Wallis] I like that one. - [Clara] Mm-hmm.

259
00:15:41,365 --> 00:15:43,400
Al, can you show us where it is?

260
00:15:44,067 --> 00:15:46,436
I wish I could, baby, but I don't remember.

261
00:15:47,771 --> 00:15:48,972
Was it close?

262
00:15:49,606 --> 00:15:52,709
Well, I believe we walked there so it couldn't be too far.

263
00:15:55,379 --> 00:15:58,482
[all chuckling]

264
00:16:00,150 --> 00:16:03,553
Alexa, Jamie, you all need to keep track

265
00:16:03,687 --> 00:16:05,088
of where you are out there, okay?

266
00:16:05,222 --> 00:16:07,724
It's real easy to get lost in them woods, and baby,

267
00:16:07,858 --> 00:16:09,459
if you do find that tree,

268
00:16:10,160 --> 00:16:11,962
don't go wishing you was someplace else

269
00:16:12,095 --> 00:16:13,897
without telling me first, okay?

270
00:16:14,531 --> 00:16:16,366
'Cause you know your daddy don't believe in all that magic stuff.

271
00:16:16,533 --> 00:16:18,969
He's just gonna think you've been kidnapped, all right?

272
00:16:19,436 --> 00:16:21,371
- There we go. - Can we go now?

273
00:16:21,538 --> 00:16:24,107
Uh-huh. Couple of bananas. There you go.

274
00:16:24,608 --> 00:16:26,310
- Have a good time. - Okay.

275
00:16:30,247 --> 00:16:31,848
That'll keep 'em busy for a while.

276
00:16:32,082 --> 00:16:33,684
[Wallis chuckles]

277
00:16:36,086 --> 00:16:37,788
You know, I think it's cruel to send them out looking

278
00:16:37,921 --> 00:16:39,823
for something you know they're never gonna find.

279
00:16:40,123 --> 00:16:41,525
Oh, come on, Clara, they're kids,

280
00:16:41,658 --> 00:16:42,826
they're gonna have fun trying.

281
00:16:43,260 --> 00:16:44,461
Excuse me.

282
00:16:45,329 --> 00:16:47,664
But what makes you two believe they'll never find that tree?

283
00:16:47,798 --> 00:16:49,032
[Wallis chuckles]

284
00:16:49,166 --> 00:16:52,002
Goodness gracious, Professor, you sound like Mama.

285
00:16:53,670 --> 00:16:54,805
What's wrong, Clara?

286
00:16:55,439 --> 00:16:57,341
You too grown up to believe in magic?

287
00:17:00,377 --> 00:17:01,411
[Wallis chuckles]

288
00:17:06,350 --> 00:17:09,353
I wish I was six feet tall.

289
00:17:12,689 --> 00:17:13,890
Mark it.

290
00:17:18,128 --> 00:17:21,331
What are we gonna do if you really turn six feet tall?

291
00:17:21,465 --> 00:17:24,201
Just wish myself back to normal, I guess.

292
00:17:24,334 --> 00:17:26,336
What if you only get one wish?

293
00:17:26,670 --> 00:17:27,871
I dunno.

294
00:17:28,505 --> 00:17:30,340
I guess you'll have to wish me back.

295
00:17:30,540 --> 00:17:33,343
Do you think I'm gonna waste my one wish on that?

296
00:17:33,477 --> 00:17:35,679
- I'd do it for you! - Would not!

297
00:17:35,812 --> 00:17:36,880
Would too!

298
00:17:37,014 --> 00:17:38,882
- Would you, really? - Mm-hmm.

299
00:17:40,083 --> 00:17:43,520
Well then, I guess I'd do it for you too.

300
00:17:46,356 --> 00:17:52,195
I wish...I wish I never had to eat broccoli again.

301
00:17:53,363 --> 00:17:57,367
We spent most of that afternoon repotting her plants.

302
00:17:58,568 --> 00:18:02,139
In the process, she made certain that I learned

303
00:18:02,272 --> 00:18:03,840
the names of all of them.

304
00:18:06,043 --> 00:18:08,278
She said it would make them more comfortable.

305
00:18:08,845 --> 00:18:12,549
Afterwards, she thanked me with a kiss on the cheek

306
00:18:14,151 --> 00:18:17,754
and then went in for her five o'clock nap.

307
00:18:21,024 --> 00:18:26,063
I realize now that somehow she knew her time had come.

308
00:18:26,897 --> 00:18:28,799
[birds cawing]

309
00:18:28,932 --> 00:18:31,568
[gentle music]

310
00:18:44,848 --> 00:18:46,650
I can almost hear her humming.

311
00:18:51,788 --> 00:18:54,591
You know, a while back, I tried to start a catalog

312
00:18:54,724 --> 00:18:56,359
of your mother's stories.

313
00:18:56,493 --> 00:18:59,096
Unfortunately, she didn't care too much for talking

314
00:18:59,229 --> 00:19:02,065
to a camera, so this is about as far as we got.

315
00:19:02,199 --> 00:19:05,001
- "Jenny and Joe." - Yeah, I remember that one.

316
00:19:05,135 --> 00:19:08,505
That was about that boy in the Civil War who got killed.

317
00:19:08,638 --> 00:19:10,207
But he came back as an angel.

318
00:19:10,340 --> 00:19:12,275
Yes, to look after his lovely bride.

319
00:19:12,409 --> 00:19:13,777
Yeah, I always thought it was so sad.

320
00:19:13,910 --> 00:19:15,645
I thought it'd make a good movie, you know?

321
00:19:15,779 --> 00:19:16,880
[Professor chuckles]

322
00:19:17,013 --> 00:19:20,717
Oh, "The Secret Life of Louise," "Dolphin."

323
00:19:20,884 --> 00:19:24,387
Oh, look, it's "The Wishing Tree."

324
00:19:25,989 --> 00:19:27,557
"The Wishing Tree."

325
00:19:27,691 --> 00:19:29,826
Oh, ah.

326
00:19:30,293 --> 00:19:35,332
More thoughts on the tree that doesn't exist.

327
00:19:36,333 --> 00:19:40,737
This is the journal of a one Able Williams.

328
00:19:40,904 --> 00:19:44,708
Owned a cotton plantation just outside Savannah.

329
00:19:46,810 --> 00:19:50,213
August 17th, 1851, I marked the page.

330
00:19:51,681 --> 00:19:55,185
"Another windstorm last night,

331
00:19:55,318 --> 00:19:58,021
Celia, Jessie's daughter, tried to run.

332
00:19:58,388 --> 00:20:00,957
The dogs caught up with her down near the river

333
00:20:01,091 --> 00:20:03,160
and chased her up a tree.

334
00:20:03,293 --> 00:20:07,297
By the time we got there, she was nowhere to be found.

335
00:20:07,631 --> 00:20:09,900
I'm not sure what happened to little Celia,

336
00:20:10,033 --> 00:20:13,036
but I believe the Lord himself must have taken her.

337
00:20:14,171 --> 00:20:16,773
Missing, presumed dead."

338
00:20:17,307 --> 00:20:18,575
It's very interesting, Professor,

339
00:20:18,708 --> 00:20:21,511
but it's hardly proof of a magical tree.

340
00:20:22,312 --> 00:20:23,580
Well, you must admit, Clara,

341
00:20:23,713 --> 00:20:26,316
that something unusual happened that night.

342
00:20:26,650 --> 00:20:29,286
Yeah, of course. A young girl escaped slavery.

343
00:20:29,753 --> 00:20:30,987
Look at you two.

344
00:20:31,121 --> 00:20:32,689
Can you once agree on something?

345
00:20:33,290 --> 00:20:36,359
Well, I'll grant that Clara may very well be right.

346
00:20:36,860 --> 00:20:38,128
Yet at the same time,

347
00:20:38,261 --> 00:20:40,564
I think she should open her mind to the possibility

348
00:20:40,697 --> 00:20:42,465
that she just might be wrong.

349
00:20:42,599 --> 00:20:45,235
[gentle music]

350
00:20:49,773 --> 00:20:51,808
Would you two excuse me, please?

351
00:20:56,613 --> 00:20:57,814
Did I say something wrong?

352
00:20:57,948 --> 00:21:01,418
No Daddy, I just... she just needs a moment.

353
00:21:01,918 --> 00:21:03,720
[bird cawing]

354
00:21:04,854 --> 00:21:06,423
[Jamie] Celia only got one wish.

355
00:21:06,556 --> 00:21:08,058
[Alexa] She only used one.

356
00:21:08,191 --> 00:21:10,427
I bet she had at least two more coming.

357
00:21:10,560 --> 00:21:12,963
[Jamie] Well, I know what I'm gonna wish for.

358
00:21:13,096 --> 00:21:15,198
- [Alexa] What? - A hundred more wishes.

359
00:21:15,332 --> 00:21:17,400
Jamie, don't be stupid.

360
00:21:17,534 --> 00:21:19,569
The tree is gonna know if you try to cheat,

361
00:21:19,703 --> 00:21:21,538
and then you'll end up with nothing.

362
00:21:22,973 --> 00:21:24,908
We've gotta think of something good.

363
00:21:25,275 --> 00:21:27,944
You know, like something nobody else can do.

364
00:21:29,279 --> 00:21:31,748
[tense music]

365
00:21:31,881 --> 00:21:34,150
Jamie, stop, I'm trying to think.

366
00:21:34,384 --> 00:21:35,585
So am I!

367
00:21:35,719 --> 00:21:38,388
- [Alexa gasps and screams] - Shh!

368
00:21:38,788 --> 00:21:39,823
Shh!

369
00:21:41,091 --> 00:21:43,260
Shh. Shh!

370
00:21:47,597 --> 00:21:50,133
[mysterious music]

371
00:22:13,657 --> 00:22:15,825
- Wow, he's good! - Yeah.

372
00:22:16,960 --> 00:22:19,529
[gentle music]

373
00:22:25,502 --> 00:22:26,603
[Jamie blows]

374
00:22:31,007 --> 00:22:32,208
Whoa!

375
00:22:41,151 --> 00:22:43,019
Hey, you okay?

376
00:22:44,120 --> 00:22:45,188
Yeah.

377
00:22:47,057 --> 00:22:49,759
I just wish I got to see her one last time.

378
00:22:50,694 --> 00:22:51,728
Hmm.

379
00:22:52,996 --> 00:22:58,001
I imagine wherever she is, she's wishing the same thing.

380
00:23:00,170 --> 00:23:01,638
She sure missed you a lot.

381
00:23:04,874 --> 00:23:06,109
Yeah, I know.

382
00:23:08,278 --> 00:23:10,380
So how come you didn't come visit more often?

383
00:23:21,458 --> 00:23:22,926
I was busy, Wallis.

384
00:23:23,993 --> 00:23:25,528
You know, sometimes I think she thought

385
00:23:25,662 --> 00:23:27,097
you didn't come 'cause of her.

386
00:23:27,664 --> 00:23:29,632
Well, I didn't come because I didn't want

387
00:23:29,766 --> 00:23:32,802
to end up another poor, uneducated Black woman,

388
00:23:32,936 --> 00:23:34,604
dependent upon your father's charity.

389
00:23:35,405 --> 00:23:36,873
Why is that so hard to understand?

390
00:23:37,006 --> 00:23:38,375
My father's charity?

391
00:23:39,109 --> 00:23:41,244
[chuckles] What are you talking about?

392
00:23:42,812 --> 00:23:43,913
Oh, come on.

393
00:23:44,848 --> 00:23:46,783
You heard him today at the service.

394
00:23:47,183 --> 00:23:49,419
After all they've been through, after all this time,

395
00:23:49,552 --> 00:23:51,421
all he could say about my mother was,

396
00:23:51,554 --> 00:23:55,091
she was some poor Black woman showed up on his doorstep

397
00:23:55,225 --> 00:23:57,527
with a baby in her arms, looking for a job.

398
00:23:57,660 --> 00:23:59,963
My father loved your mother.

399
00:24:00,363 --> 00:24:01,931
He didn't say that, did he?

400
00:24:02,065 --> 00:24:03,466
Well, maybe not in so many words,

401
00:24:03,600 --> 00:24:06,302
but he loved her and he loves you!

402
00:24:06,436 --> 00:24:08,805
I mean, for God's sakes.

403
00:24:10,673 --> 00:24:13,610
He is more proud of you than he is of me.

404
00:24:13,743 --> 00:24:17,180
I mean, you should hear him bragging on Clara's doing this,

405
00:24:17,313 --> 00:24:19,115
and Clara's doing that, I mean.

406
00:24:20,450 --> 00:24:23,820
Well, I am very appreciative of everything he's done,

407
00:24:23,953 --> 00:24:26,356
but I am not under the illusion

408
00:24:26,523 --> 00:24:29,559
that I'm anything more than one of his projects.

409
00:24:30,927 --> 00:24:32,362
Well, if that is really how you feel,

410
00:24:32,529 --> 00:24:34,030
then I feel sorry for you.

411
00:24:34,864 --> 00:24:36,499
Because with all your big education,

412
00:24:37,934 --> 00:24:39,602
you don't know anything about love.

413
00:24:41,004 --> 00:24:44,374
[gentle music]

414
00:24:54,918 --> 00:24:56,853
[dog barking]

415
00:24:58,988 --> 00:25:01,124
Clara, we found him!

416
00:25:01,257 --> 00:25:02,392
Found who, sweetie?

417
00:25:02,559 --> 00:25:03,960
[Alexa] The man you told us about!

418
00:25:04,160 --> 00:25:05,762
The one out in the woods.

419
00:25:05,895 --> 00:25:08,031
Ah, you did?

420
00:25:08,264 --> 00:25:10,500
- [Jamie] And guess what, Clara? - What?

421
00:25:10,800 --> 00:25:14,370
- He's magic too. - Really?

422
00:25:14,971 --> 00:25:16,339
You wanna meet him?

423
00:25:16,673 --> 00:25:18,875
No, I really have to get back to Atlanta.

424
00:25:20,343 --> 00:25:22,946
Can't you go back tomorrow?

425
00:25:24,647 --> 00:25:26,483
- [Alexa] Please, Clara? - Now kids, you heard

426
00:25:26,616 --> 00:25:28,184
what Clara said, she has to get back to work,

427
00:25:28,318 --> 00:25:29,619
and you need to wash your hands.

428
00:25:29,752 --> 00:25:31,254
Come on, we're gonna eat supper in a few minutes.

429
00:25:31,387 --> 00:25:32,822
Go on, skip.

430
00:25:32,956 --> 00:25:35,058
Quick like a bunny, let's go, Jamie, come on.

431
00:25:35,358 --> 00:25:37,961
- A bunny isn't too quick. - Well, he's pretty quick.

432
00:25:40,196 --> 00:25:42,365
You know, you're welcome to stay for dinner if you like.

433
00:25:43,600 --> 00:25:44,634
Thanks.

434
00:25:45,468 --> 00:25:47,804
But I really think I'd better get on the road

435
00:25:47,937 --> 00:25:49,038
while it's still light.

436
00:25:50,173 --> 00:25:51,841
Yeah, I guess that would be safer.

437
00:26:02,485 --> 00:26:04,521
Come on, scoot now, come on, out you get.

438
00:26:04,654 --> 00:26:05,989
[dog barking]

439
00:26:07,657 --> 00:26:08,825
Anything else?

440
00:26:09,025 --> 00:26:10,293
No, thanks.

441
00:26:13,162 --> 00:26:14,230
Godspeed.

442
00:26:14,364 --> 00:26:15,665
- Okay. - Mm-hmm.

443
00:26:16,900 --> 00:26:18,668
I don't want you staying too long between visits,

444
00:26:18,801 --> 00:26:19,836
do you hear?

445
00:26:23,740 --> 00:26:24,841
Love you, honey.

446
00:26:25,675 --> 00:26:27,911
[gentle music]

447
00:26:37,153 --> 00:26:39,188
[car engine starting]

448
00:26:40,056 --> 00:26:43,126
[music continues]

449
00:26:55,838 --> 00:26:59,042
[bird screeching]

450
00:27:01,244 --> 00:27:04,080
[tense music]

451
00:27:24,267 --> 00:27:26,769
[bird screeching]

452
00:27:36,079 --> 00:27:38,348
[dog barking]

453
00:27:39,582 --> 00:27:40,583
Bean!

454
00:27:40,883 --> 00:27:42,085
Bean!

455
00:27:42,485 --> 00:27:44,087
What are you doing?

456
00:27:44,320 --> 00:27:46,089
[dog barking]

457
00:27:52,962 --> 00:27:54,297
I'm sorry.

458
00:27:55,231 --> 00:27:56,466
I'm sorry, come on.

459
00:27:56,699 --> 00:27:59,035
Come here, come here, baby.

460
00:27:59,669 --> 00:28:02,472
I'm sorry, I'm sorry, little guy.

461
00:28:03,539 --> 00:28:05,575
Bean, I was on my way to Atlanta.

462
00:28:05,708 --> 00:28:06,809
You live in Savannah.

463
00:28:08,177 --> 00:28:09,212
[sighs]

464
00:28:09,345 --> 00:28:11,147
Supposed to be in Savannah.

465
00:28:14,150 --> 00:28:15,952
[owl hooting]

466
00:28:23,693 --> 00:28:26,195
[dog barking]

467
00:28:27,296 --> 00:28:29,699
Stop that barking, stop that.

468
00:28:30,533 --> 00:28:32,769
[Clara speaking indistinctly]

469
00:28:33,036 --> 00:28:34,070
[dog barking]

470
00:28:39,275 --> 00:28:40,343
Hey, Bean.

471
00:28:41,377 --> 00:28:44,013
I was about an hour outside of Atlanta

472
00:28:44,147 --> 00:28:45,748
and he jumped over the backseat.

473
00:28:46,349 --> 00:28:48,785
Well, thanks for bringing him back.

474
00:28:49,385 --> 00:28:51,854
Just made a fresh pot of tea.

475
00:28:51,988 --> 00:28:53,456
You care to join me?

476
00:28:55,291 --> 00:28:56,859
I don't know why.

477
00:28:56,993 --> 00:28:58,361
I guess I'm losing my mind,

478
00:28:58,494 --> 00:29:02,432
but I keep feeling like,

479
00:29:03,666 --> 00:29:07,870
like, um... like Mama's still here.

480
00:29:09,172 --> 00:29:11,240
And I know this is strange,

481
00:29:11,374 --> 00:29:17,046
but I keep feeling like she doesn't want me to leave.

482
00:29:17,213 --> 00:29:21,350
No, no, I don't think that's strange.

483
00:29:21,484 --> 00:29:22,585
Not one bit.

484
00:29:22,719 --> 00:29:26,889
I just...I know she's here.

485
00:29:27,356 --> 00:29:28,524
I can feel her.

486
00:29:29,358 --> 00:29:31,060
I can. Every day.

487
00:29:32,595 --> 00:29:35,631
And I miss her.

488
00:29:36,799 --> 00:29:38,301
I miss her so bad.

489
00:29:40,236 --> 00:29:43,306
[both crying]

490
00:29:48,878 --> 00:29:50,213
[Wallis sighs]

491
00:29:50,346 --> 00:29:52,849
[bird cawing]

492
00:30:00,423 --> 00:30:02,759
So is this how y'all spend the afternoons?

493
00:30:04,360 --> 00:30:06,529
Listen, honey, you're not Southern

494
00:30:06,662 --> 00:30:09,599
if you can't sit and do nothing for a little while.

495
00:30:10,600 --> 00:30:13,469
Are you writing country music or are you talking to me?

496
00:30:14,070 --> 00:30:17,306
Well, I think Phil's point, Clara,

497
00:30:17,440 --> 00:30:22,178
is that sometimes it's nice just to slow down a little bit.

498
00:30:22,311 --> 00:30:25,314
Any slower than this and you'll be dead, darling.

499
00:30:25,548 --> 00:30:27,016
[chuckles] Well, all right then.

500
00:30:27,850 --> 00:30:29,118
All right, come on.

501
00:30:29,252 --> 00:30:30,853
We got plenty to do in the garden.

502
00:30:30,987 --> 00:30:33,055
Oh no, you have got to be kidding.

503
00:30:33,222 --> 00:30:34,857
I don't believe she is, Clara.

504
00:30:35,424 --> 00:30:36,692
Come on.

505
00:30:37,560 --> 00:30:40,496
[gentle music]

506
00:30:45,668 --> 00:30:47,170
[turkey gobbling]

507
00:30:51,641 --> 00:30:54,277
[music continues]

508
00:31:02,051 --> 00:31:03,186
Did you make this?

509
00:31:05,488 --> 00:31:07,089
It's pretty cool.

510
00:31:08,791 --> 00:31:11,093
Magic Man, how come you live out here,

511
00:31:11,661 --> 00:31:13,396
so far away from everything?

512
00:31:15,798 --> 00:31:17,033
Don't you get lonely?

513
00:31:20,069 --> 00:31:23,039
Well, don't you have any friends?

514
00:31:25,074 --> 00:31:27,710
[gentle music]

515
00:31:45,561 --> 00:31:47,330
Now, this was one of Mama Mattie's secrets

516
00:31:47,463 --> 00:31:48,965
for keeping the raccoons away.

517
00:31:49,665 --> 00:31:51,500
She said you bury three cloves of garlic

518
00:31:51,634 --> 00:31:53,202
real close to the base of each plant

519
00:31:53,336 --> 00:31:54,770
and leave them there for one week.

520
00:31:55,771 --> 00:31:57,573
You know they sell these at the grocery.

521
00:31:57,707 --> 00:31:58,908
Yeah, I know that.

522
00:32:00,710 --> 00:32:02,044
Like Mama Mattie always said,

523
00:32:02,178 --> 00:32:04,280
they taste better when you grow 'em yourself, mm.

524
00:32:04,413 --> 00:32:06,883
- [Jamie] Hey, hey! - Mm, mm!

525
00:32:08,851 --> 00:32:10,553
Hey, you kids, what y'all doing?

526
00:32:10,853 --> 00:32:13,289
- Nothing. - Well then,

527
00:32:13,422 --> 00:32:15,057
Al and Marianne, they're looking for you.

528
00:32:15,191 --> 00:32:16,726
They got something they wanna show you.

529
00:32:16,859 --> 00:32:18,094
- What is it? - I don't know.

530
00:32:18,227 --> 00:32:20,897
I guess you're gonna have to go and find out for yourself.

531
00:32:24,767 --> 00:32:26,903
Hey, Clara. You wanna come with us?

532
00:32:28,571 --> 00:32:29,906
Can you do without me?

533
00:32:30,606 --> 00:32:33,809
- Well, I guess I can. - Coming!

534
00:32:38,681 --> 00:32:40,917
- So, Clara? - Yes.

535
00:32:41,083 --> 00:32:44,186
What else did your mom say about that man in the woods?

536
00:32:44,420 --> 00:32:46,355
I don't remember much.

537
00:32:46,956 --> 00:32:48,291
Why do you ask?

538
00:32:48,424 --> 00:32:51,193
I'm just wondering if it's the same guy we found.

539
00:32:51,761 --> 00:32:53,429
Hm, I don't know.

540
00:32:53,562 --> 00:32:55,298
Were you lost when you met him?

541
00:32:55,631 --> 00:32:56,832
No.

542
00:32:56,966 --> 00:32:58,501
It was probably not the same one.

543
00:32:58,701 --> 00:33:00,970
'Cause the one my mama told me about

544
00:33:01,103 --> 00:33:03,472
- only came if you got lost. - Hmm.

545
00:33:05,775 --> 00:33:07,343
[Clara] Where are we going?

546
00:33:08,711 --> 00:33:12,481
[Marianne humming]

547
00:33:15,017 --> 00:33:16,352
Clara, maybe you should take a seat.

548
00:33:16,485 --> 00:33:17,586
You look a little pale.

549
00:33:20,723 --> 00:33:22,959
Is this really for a cookbook?

550
00:33:23,192 --> 00:33:26,862
Oh, it's more than a cookbook, dear.

551
00:33:28,431 --> 00:33:30,766
It's critter cuisine.

552
00:33:31,367 --> 00:33:33,302
You think people will like it?

553
00:33:33,769 --> 00:33:34,937
Of course they will.

554
00:33:35,905 --> 00:33:40,176
I had armadillo with a nice worm sauce last night.

555
00:33:41,210 --> 00:33:44,146
Best meal I've had in years.

556
00:33:44,280 --> 00:33:45,715
[Marianne] Al, stop it.

557
00:33:46,048 --> 00:33:48,217
This is not for a real cookbook, kids.

558
00:33:48,351 --> 00:33:49,518
It's just a joke.

559
00:33:49,952 --> 00:33:51,187
Marianne!

560
00:33:51,320 --> 00:33:52,388
You didn't tell me.

561
00:33:53,522 --> 00:33:55,891
[Marianne chuckles]

562
00:33:56,025 --> 00:33:59,462
So, when are you two gonna get married?

563
00:34:00,129 --> 00:34:01,864
Not till after college.

564
00:34:01,998 --> 00:34:03,032
[Al] Yeah?

565
00:34:03,933 --> 00:34:06,369
That's about the time me and the missus first tied the knot.

566
00:34:07,470 --> 00:34:11,240
You know, it'll be 30 years next week.

567
00:34:11,807 --> 00:34:12,842
Wow.

568
00:34:12,975 --> 00:34:14,210
Congratulations.

569
00:34:14,610 --> 00:34:16,512
Oh, we're planning a big party.

570
00:34:16,645 --> 00:34:17,747
If you're still here then, Clara,

571
00:34:17,880 --> 00:34:19,348
we'd love for you to join us.

572
00:34:19,715 --> 00:34:21,550
Thank you, I'd be honored.

573
00:34:21,684 --> 00:34:24,653
So, you guys wanna know the secret

574
00:34:24,787 --> 00:34:26,255
of making the marriage last?

575
00:34:26,756 --> 00:34:27,857
Okay.

576
00:34:27,990 --> 00:34:30,559
Well, it's actually pretty simple.

577
00:34:32,895 --> 00:34:33,929
Laughter.

578
00:34:34,563 --> 00:34:36,032
If you're making each other laugh,

579
00:34:36,399 --> 00:34:37,933
you're making each other happy.

580
00:34:38,067 --> 00:34:39,969
- Ain't that right, honey? - Mm-hmm.

581
00:34:41,237 --> 00:34:43,539
Of course, the missus here ain't all that funny.

582
00:34:44,006 --> 00:34:46,409
So sometimes I have to pretend.

583
00:34:46,809 --> 00:34:48,077
But that's easy.

584
00:34:48,411 --> 00:34:49,645
Go ahead, honey, say something.

585
00:34:50,980 --> 00:34:52,214
I'll show you funny, mister,

586
00:34:52,348 --> 00:34:54,283
just as soon as these children here leave.

587
00:34:54,450 --> 00:34:57,386
[laughs]

588
00:34:59,822 --> 00:35:00,890
See?

589
00:35:01,023 --> 00:35:02,091
That's all it takes.

590
00:35:02,725 --> 00:35:03,759
[both giggle]

591
00:35:03,893 --> 00:35:05,628
[Marianne laughs]

592
00:35:05,928 --> 00:35:08,230
He is funny, isn't he?

593
00:35:08,364 --> 00:35:10,266
That's why I love him so much.

594
00:35:10,866 --> 00:35:12,101
Come here, baby.

595
00:35:12,234 --> 00:35:13,235
Give me a hug.

596
00:35:13,736 --> 00:35:15,871
[Marianne laughs]

597
00:35:18,307 --> 00:35:19,875
Ah, ah!

598
00:35:20,009 --> 00:35:21,744
Oh, oh!

599
00:35:21,877 --> 00:35:24,980
[all laughing]

600
00:35:39,395 --> 00:35:40,796
Lord, what a mess.

601
00:35:40,930 --> 00:35:42,598
I have no idea what these kids were thinking.

602
00:35:43,332 --> 00:35:45,901
They packed enough food here to feed an army.

603
00:35:46,035 --> 00:35:47,103
[Clara] You know, I'm a lawyer.

604
00:35:47,236 --> 00:35:48,904
Why am I the one who's gotta wash the dishes?

605
00:35:49,038 --> 00:35:50,806
Oh, you may be a lawyer, but you're my little poobly--

606
00:35:50,940 --> 00:35:52,842
[laughs] Get the phone, will you?

607
00:35:53,109 --> 00:35:55,211
- [Wallis laughs] - [Clara speaks indistinctly]

608
00:35:55,344 --> 00:35:56,378
Hello?

609
00:35:57,880 --> 00:35:58,948
Oh, hi, Phil.

610
00:36:00,516 --> 00:36:01,717
No, they're not here.

611
00:36:03,152 --> 00:36:04,186
Uh-huh.

612
00:36:06,288 --> 00:36:07,857
She think they took her sheets.

613
00:36:08,591 --> 00:36:09,625
Her sheets?

614
00:36:10,426 --> 00:36:13,295
Oh, excuse me. Her Ralph Loren sheets.

615
00:36:14,263 --> 00:36:15,798
So, wh--

616
00:36:16,232 --> 00:36:18,033
Oh, Ralph Lauren sheets.

617
00:36:18,167 --> 00:36:19,468
[Wallis chuckles]

618
00:36:29,478 --> 00:36:31,180
I couldn't find the picnic blanket.

619
00:36:31,313 --> 00:36:33,015
So this will have to do.

620
00:36:33,749 --> 00:36:35,518
We've got tons of stuff.

621
00:36:35,718 --> 00:36:38,320
Turkey, ham, roast beef.

622
00:36:38,854 --> 00:36:40,322
Cheese and crackers.

623
00:36:40,990 --> 00:36:42,825
And three different kinds of bread.

624
00:36:42,958 --> 00:36:45,161
'Cause we didn't know which one you'd like.

625
00:36:52,801 --> 00:36:55,004
[birds singing]

626
00:36:57,706 --> 00:36:59,141
Alexa!

627
00:37:02,945 --> 00:37:04,213
Jamie!

628
00:37:20,229 --> 00:37:22,565
What should we do with the rest of the food?

629
00:37:30,339 --> 00:37:33,342
[clicking tongue]

630
00:37:38,380 --> 00:37:39,648
[clicks tongue]

631
00:37:39,782 --> 00:37:41,617
[gentle music]

632
00:37:57,633 --> 00:38:00,769
[tense music]

633
00:38:15,384 --> 00:38:16,552
What are y'all doing?

634
00:38:18,354 --> 00:38:19,421
Uh-oh.

635
00:38:20,656 --> 00:38:22,324
What are you all doing out here?

636
00:38:22,758 --> 00:38:25,160
We were feeding a deer until you showed up.

637
00:38:26,195 --> 00:38:27,630
Yeah, I noticed that.

638
00:38:32,468 --> 00:38:33,769
Is this a friend of yours?

639
00:38:34,136 --> 00:38:35,504
Yeah, it's Magic Man.

640
00:38:35,638 --> 00:38:37,139
The one we told you about.

641
00:38:40,209 --> 00:38:42,011
I don't remember you telling me about anybody.

642
00:38:42,578 --> 00:38:44,580
[Alexa] Clara, yes we did.

643
00:38:45,814 --> 00:38:47,816
Did I see you out by the highway the other day?

644
00:38:50,953 --> 00:38:52,955
Right, so you live around here?

645
00:38:53,489 --> 00:38:56,558
[Alexa] Clara, we told you, he lives out in the woods.

646
00:38:56,692 --> 00:38:58,294
Baby, let the man do his own talking.

647
00:38:58,794 --> 00:39:01,864
He can't, Clara, he can't talk.

648
00:39:05,934 --> 00:39:08,137
Oh, I didn't know.

649
00:39:13,309 --> 00:39:15,511
I think he said it's nice to meet ya.

650
00:39:25,688 --> 00:39:27,222
It's nice to meet you, too.

651
00:39:29,491 --> 00:39:30,559
Magic Man.

652
00:39:35,698 --> 00:39:37,333
Does your mother know about this man?

653
00:39:37,466 --> 00:39:38,867
No, and you can't tell her.

654
00:39:39,268 --> 00:39:40,469
Why not?

655
00:39:40,803 --> 00:39:43,005
Because she might think he's weird or something

656
00:39:43,138 --> 00:39:45,207
and not let us play with him.

657
00:39:45,808 --> 00:39:47,710
Well, she might be right, Jamie.

658
00:39:47,843 --> 00:39:49,678
Well, do you think he's weird?

659
00:39:50,612 --> 00:39:54,049
No, I don't know, he seems like a nice man.

660
00:39:55,317 --> 00:39:59,088
Okay then, you've gotta swear to secrecy.

661
00:39:59,555 --> 00:40:00,789
Why?

662
00:40:00,923 --> 00:40:04,560
Because, we've gotta know you're not going to tell.

663
00:40:04,693 --> 00:40:06,495
No, why secrecy?

664
00:40:06,628 --> 00:40:08,530
Your mother will probably think he's fine too,

665
00:40:08,664 --> 00:40:10,966
- if she meets him. - No, he's too shy.

666
00:40:11,100 --> 00:40:13,369
He doesn't wanna meet anyone else.

667
00:40:13,502 --> 00:40:15,804
You've gotta swear, Clara.

668
00:40:16,338 --> 00:40:18,540
I'm not swearing to anything.

669
00:40:18,674 --> 00:40:19,908
I don't really know him.

670
00:40:21,343 --> 00:40:22,878
But I tell you what I will do.

671
00:40:23,879 --> 00:40:25,748
I'll keep a secret if you two promise

672
00:40:25,881 --> 00:40:27,916
not to go and see him without me.

673
00:40:30,185 --> 00:40:31,587
Do we have a deal?

674
00:40:31,720 --> 00:40:33,856
- Yeah. - Okay.

675
00:40:34,857 --> 00:40:35,891
Good.

676
00:40:36,959 --> 00:40:38,994
And by the way, you two are in a heap of trouble

677
00:40:39,128 --> 00:40:41,230
for taking all that stuff from the house.

678
00:40:42,131 --> 00:40:43,499
But luckily for you,

679
00:40:43,632 --> 00:40:46,702
I am an attorney and I might be able to get you out of it.

680
00:40:48,404 --> 00:40:50,606
I didn't know they're your favorite sheets, Mom,

681
00:40:50,739 --> 00:40:52,141
or else I wouldn't have taken them.

682
00:40:52,608 --> 00:40:53,876
Mm.

683
00:40:54,410 --> 00:40:56,412
[Alexa] We just want something to build a fort with.

684
00:40:57,079 --> 00:40:59,314
But Clara's took us shopping and look,

685
00:40:59,448 --> 00:41:01,116
we got you the same ones.

686
00:41:01,250 --> 00:41:02,284
Ralph Lauren.

687
00:41:02,451 --> 00:41:04,420
Oh, well, isn't that sweet?

688
00:41:05,854 --> 00:41:08,357
[Jamie] We also went grocery shopping, Mama,

689
00:41:08,724 --> 00:41:10,592
and bought a bunch of new food.

690
00:41:10,726 --> 00:41:12,661
But Jamie, that is not the point.

691
00:41:12,795 --> 00:41:15,731
I even got you Ben and Jerry's Chunky Monkey,

692
00:41:16,098 --> 00:41:17,766
'cause I know it's your favorite.

693
00:41:17,966 --> 00:41:19,334
[Wallis] Now you listen to me young man.

694
00:41:19,468 --> 00:41:22,938
You do not go taking things without asking for them first.

695
00:41:23,071 --> 00:41:25,174
We don't do those things around this house.

696
00:41:31,647 --> 00:41:32,948
I'm sorry, Mom.

697
00:41:35,918 --> 00:41:39,588
Well now, did somebody say something about Chunky Monkey?

698
00:41:40,789 --> 00:41:42,858
All right, I guess we'll just forget about all this,

699
00:41:42,991 --> 00:41:44,226
and have us some ice cream!

700
00:41:44,359 --> 00:41:48,464
I scream, you scream, we all scream for ice cream!

701
00:41:48,630 --> 00:41:49,898
- [Jamie] Yay! - [Wallis laughs]

702
00:41:50,032 --> 00:41:51,667
- Have you had some already? - [Alexa] Go, let's go!

703
00:41:51,800 --> 00:41:53,135
[Wallis] You're getting heavy, come on.

704
00:41:55,671 --> 00:41:59,241
- [thunder rumbling] - [mysterious music]

705
00:42:07,516 --> 00:42:10,085
[rain pattering]

706
00:42:19,127 --> 00:42:21,797
[thunder rumbling]

707
00:42:25,367 --> 00:42:28,871
[tense music]

708
00:42:29,004 --> 00:42:31,640
[birds calling]

709
00:42:38,814 --> 00:42:40,516
[water splashing]

710
00:42:45,554 --> 00:42:46,922
[imitating bird call]

711
00:42:50,225 --> 00:42:52,361
[imitating bird call]

712
00:42:53,562 --> 00:42:56,598
[mysterious music]

713
00:43:20,822 --> 00:43:24,226
What they didn't know is that little Celia

714
00:43:24,359 --> 00:43:26,962
had found the wishing tree.

715
00:43:27,629 --> 00:43:31,066
A tree like none other in the world.

716
00:43:31,633 --> 00:43:37,072
So when she said, "Please, please don't let them get me,"

717
00:43:38,273 --> 00:43:41,810
the tree granted her wish and took her away.

718
00:43:43,245 --> 00:43:44,746
A couple of days later,

719
00:43:44,880 --> 00:43:48,517
she awoke beneath a towering elm tree.

720
00:43:49,384 --> 00:43:53,488
And what little Celia probably thought was heaven

721
00:43:53,622 --> 00:43:56,058
turned out to be Philadelphia.

722
00:43:57,192 --> 00:44:00,963
Imagine that, thinking any place up north was heaven.

723
00:44:01,096 --> 00:44:02,965
[chuckles]

724
00:44:04,066 --> 00:44:07,603
[laughs] Oh, I'm just kidding.

725
00:44:08,604 --> 00:44:10,339
I hear it's nice up there.

726
00:44:10,472 --> 00:44:11,707
[Professor on tape] Tell me something.

727
00:44:11,907 --> 00:44:13,775
Why is it that all your stories

728
00:44:13,909 --> 00:44:15,477
seem to be set in Georgia?

729
00:44:16,445 --> 00:44:18,146
Oh, Professor.

730
00:44:18,313 --> 00:44:19,548
[chuckles]

731
00:44:20,515 --> 00:44:22,918
I don't just live in Georgia.

732
00:44:23,352 --> 00:44:25,554
Georgia lives in me.

733
00:44:26,088 --> 00:44:27,289
[Professor on tape] I'm sorry.

734
00:44:28,123 --> 00:44:29,625
I'm afraid I don't understand.

735
00:44:29,891 --> 00:44:31,660
[chuckles]

736
00:44:31,793 --> 00:44:33,195
I doubt you would.

737
00:44:34,262 --> 00:44:36,632
Even if I explained it.

738
00:44:40,936 --> 00:44:43,171
I still don't know what the hell she meant by that.

739
00:44:48,377 --> 00:44:51,413
Go on, go on, I think there's another one on there.

740
00:44:54,650 --> 00:44:56,118
[Mattie on tape] Okay.

741
00:44:56,251 --> 00:44:58,487
I think we've got time for one more.

742
00:45:01,823 --> 00:45:05,360
Oh, here's a good one.

743
00:45:07,162 --> 00:45:08,530
This-- [clears throat]

744
00:45:08,664 --> 00:45:13,869
This was one of Clara's favorites when she was little.

745
00:45:15,504 --> 00:45:18,040
She called it "The Dreamer."

746
00:45:20,275 --> 00:45:22,010
Not too long ago,

747
00:45:22,144 --> 00:45:26,214
there was a boy by the name of Alvin Bailey,

748
00:45:26,982 --> 00:45:29,351
who lived out on Tybee Island.

749
00:45:29,484 --> 00:45:30,719
[gentle music]

750
00:45:30,852 --> 00:45:33,855
Now Alvin had what his mother liked to call

751
00:45:33,989 --> 00:45:36,258
an active imagination.

752
00:45:36,958 --> 00:45:41,463
You see, Alvin used to lie all the time.

753
00:45:42,364 --> 00:45:45,534
When he didn't chop the wood like he was supposed to,

754
00:45:45,667 --> 00:45:48,737
Alvin came up with a story about how a bear

755
00:45:48,870 --> 00:45:51,173
ran off with the ax.

756
00:45:51,773 --> 00:45:55,444
And when he broke his father's watch,

757
00:45:56,211 --> 00:45:59,414
he blamed it on a ghost who lived up in the attic.

758
00:45:59,548 --> 00:46:03,552
Now, little Alvin went on for years and years like this,

759
00:46:03,685 --> 00:46:06,221
making up excuses for everything.

760
00:46:06,354 --> 00:46:09,191
Till one night, he had a dream.

761
00:46:09,725 --> 00:46:14,629
He dreamt about a big tree falling on the barn

762
00:46:14,763 --> 00:46:16,898
and smashing it to pieces.

763
00:46:17,365 --> 00:46:21,603
Well, the next day, a storm came through

764
00:46:21,737 --> 00:46:24,673
and just like in Alvin's dream,

765
00:46:24,806 --> 00:46:28,944
a tree fell and smashed that barn to bits.

766
00:46:29,077 --> 00:46:33,782
Now, little Alvin carried on like you wouldn't believe.

767
00:46:35,417 --> 00:46:36,651
But no one believed.

768
00:46:37,552 --> 00:46:41,556
No one believed that his dream had come true.

769
00:46:52,067 --> 00:46:53,101
Clara?

770
00:46:55,737 --> 00:46:56,772
Yeah?

771
00:46:57,472 --> 00:46:58,573
You okay?

772
00:46:58,940 --> 00:47:01,877
Oh, I'm just doing nothing, y'all.

773
00:47:04,079 --> 00:47:05,480
[Wallis chuckles]

774
00:47:08,683 --> 00:47:10,685
- Hey, you ready? - [Alexa] Yeah.

775
00:47:12,087 --> 00:47:14,256
Um, we'll be back in a bit.

776
00:47:14,389 --> 00:47:16,024
We're going to look for the wishing tree.

777
00:47:18,093 --> 00:47:20,295
[gentle music]

778
00:47:20,462 --> 00:47:22,063
[Alexa] Come on, Jamie!

779
00:47:30,172 --> 00:47:33,341
[music continues]

780
00:47:57,833 --> 00:48:00,535
[Clara screams]

781
00:48:06,374 --> 00:48:08,009
A fish, and a big one!

782
00:48:08,143 --> 00:48:09,945
- A big fish, whoa! - [Clara screaming]

783
00:48:10,078 --> 00:48:12,214
Can I see it? Can I see it?

784
00:48:12,347 --> 00:48:15,116
- [Clara laughs] - Can I see it? Can I see it?

785
00:48:16,218 --> 00:48:17,919
[dramatic music]

786
00:48:19,855 --> 00:48:23,225
[gentle music]

787
00:48:27,529 --> 00:48:28,630
Whoa!

788
00:48:28,763 --> 00:48:29,965
[smacking lips]

789
00:48:38,740 --> 00:48:42,110
[birds singing]

790
00:48:47,749 --> 00:48:50,385
[gentle music]

791
00:49:04,065 --> 00:49:05,567
[Alexa] Magic Man.

792
00:49:06,301 --> 00:49:08,069
Can we roast some marshmallows?

793
00:49:12,974 --> 00:49:14,743
[music continues]

794
00:49:19,681 --> 00:49:20,982
So, tell me something.

795
00:49:22,117 --> 00:49:25,720
Are you known by another name, besides Magic Man?

796
00:49:30,258 --> 00:49:31,359
What is...?

797
00:49:38,400 --> 00:49:39,668
[Clara] Thomas!

798
00:49:40,936 --> 00:49:42,003
Thomas.

799
00:49:43,605 --> 00:49:44,673
Me?

800
00:49:47,242 --> 00:49:49,210
C. L.

801
00:49:58,653 --> 00:50:00,622
[chuckles]

