Thank you, Detective, goodbye.

1064
01:03:47,281 --> 01:03:48,716
Ms. Collier?

1065
01:03:48,849 --> 01:03:50,317
Until we get this fella,

1066
01:03:50,985 --> 01:03:52,686
I think you really ought to be more careful.

1067
01:04:02,163 --> 01:04:03,197
[Clara] Thomas?

1068
01:04:07,468 --> 01:04:08,536
Thomas?

1069
01:04:14,475 --> 01:04:16,477
- [tense music] - [Clara gasps]

1070
01:04:16,610 --> 01:04:17,812
Shh, shh!

1071
01:04:18,112 --> 01:04:19,146
What are you doing?

1072
01:04:20,481 --> 01:04:21,515
What?

1073
01:04:22,183 --> 01:04:23,217
What?

1074
01:04:25,886 --> 01:04:27,087
No, you stay there.

1075
01:04:30,991 --> 01:04:34,061
Thomas, I think you should go and turn yourself in.

1076
01:04:36,263 --> 01:04:39,300
Come on. You're gonna make it worse than it already is.

1077
01:04:40,701 --> 01:04:43,170
Thomas, Thomas, talk to them.

1078
01:04:44,371 --> 01:04:46,407
Why not? Why not?

1079
01:04:48,542 --> 01:04:50,544
Thomas, Thomas!

1080
01:04:54,381 --> 01:04:56,550
- [dramatic music] - [dogs barking]

1081
01:04:56,684 --> 01:04:59,019
- [man] Nothing here! - [man 2] Over there,

1082
01:04:59,153 --> 01:05:00,554
signs of life over there.

1083
01:05:01,555 --> 01:05:05,626
- [man] Thomas! - [dogs barking]

1084
01:05:05,759 --> 01:05:07,328
[man 2] Thomas, we need you to come out!

1085
01:05:07,461 --> 01:05:09,096
[dogs barking]

1086
01:05:12,366 --> 01:05:14,134
[man 3] There's a pathway down here.

1087
01:05:14,301 --> 01:05:15,336
Come on.

1088
01:05:16,503 --> 01:05:18,405
[dogs barking]

1089
01:05:18,539 --> 01:05:21,308
[officers shouting indistinctly]

1090
01:05:27,715 --> 01:05:30,150
[man] Hey, get that light over here for a sec, would you?

1091
01:05:30,351 --> 01:05:31,418
Thomas!

1092
01:05:32,119 --> 01:05:34,054
- [man 2] There he is! - [man 3] Freeze!

1093
01:05:35,222 --> 01:05:36,290
Get on your knees!

1094
01:05:38,259 --> 01:05:39,627
Put your hands behind your head!

1095
01:05:40,494 --> 01:05:42,563
[dramatic music]

1096
01:05:43,564 --> 01:05:45,099
[man 3] Down on your belly.

1097
01:05:45,232 --> 01:05:46,867
Hurry up and keep your hands still.

1098
01:05:47,568 --> 01:05:50,471
[dogs barking]

1099
01:06:18,299 --> 01:06:19,433
- [officer] Sir. - [Professor] Yeah?

1100
01:06:19,566 --> 01:06:20,968
[officer] We found Thomas.

1101
01:06:21,101 --> 01:06:23,103
He's been arrested and taken to the station for questioning.

1102
01:06:23,237 --> 01:06:24,471
[Professor] Thank goodness you got him.

1103
01:06:24,605 --> 01:06:26,307
[officer] He tried to escape, but we tracked him down.

1104
01:06:26,440 --> 01:06:27,841
- [Professor] Thank you officer. - [officer] Good night.

1105
01:06:27,975 --> 01:06:29,009
[Professor] Good night.

1106
01:06:34,782 --> 01:06:36,150
They've got him in custody.

1107
01:06:47,328 --> 01:06:48,662
You did the right thing, honey.

1108
01:06:53,934 --> 01:06:57,071
Celia put her hands on the tree and said,

1109
01:06:57,304 --> 01:07:00,374
"Please, Mister Tree, please don't let them find me."

1110
01:07:01,041 --> 01:07:03,644
So then, the wishing tree made her wish come true.

1111
01:07:04,578 --> 01:07:07,982
So by the time the mean men got there, she was gone.

1112
01:07:08,282 --> 01:07:12,019
She went up to New York and lived happily ever after.

1113
01:07:12,152 --> 01:07:13,187
The end.

1114
01:07:13,320 --> 01:07:15,389
[monitor beeping]

1115
01:07:15,522 --> 01:07:17,891
- Hey, Clara! - Hey, little girl.

1116
01:07:18,225 --> 01:07:21,095
That was a good story you told.

1117
01:07:24,298 --> 01:07:25,332
Clara.

1118
01:07:28,035 --> 01:07:29,069
Thank you.

1119
01:07:37,611 --> 01:07:39,380
- Clara? - Mm?

1120
01:07:39,513 --> 01:07:41,448
Is Magic Man in trouble?

1121
01:07:47,988 --> 01:07:49,356
Yes, sweetie, he is.

1122
01:07:49,957 --> 01:07:51,091
But you're a lawyer.

1123
01:07:51,225 --> 01:07:53,827
You can get him out of it, right?

1124
01:07:55,195 --> 01:07:58,265
He didn't do it, Clara. He would never hurt Jamie.

1125
01:07:59,967 --> 01:08:01,902
[somber music]

1126
01:08:06,840 --> 01:08:08,542
[bird screeching]

1127
01:08:10,411 --> 01:08:11,845
[tense music]

1128
01:08:12,012 --> 01:08:13,480
[bird screeching]

1129
01:08:18,419 --> 01:08:20,454
[bird screeching]

1130
01:08:28,462 --> 01:08:29,496
Hello.

1131
01:08:31,732 --> 01:08:32,766
Excuse me?

1132
01:08:34,902 --> 01:08:36,904
Officer, I'm here to see Thomas Moore.

1133
01:08:41,875 --> 01:08:42,976
[door shuts]

1134
01:08:44,611 --> 01:08:45,646
Hey, Thomas.

1135
01:08:46,513 --> 01:08:47,781
Are they treating you okay?

1136
01:08:53,420 --> 01:08:55,022
Jamie is still in the hospital.

1137
01:08:55,923 --> 01:08:57,691
He hasn't regained consciousness.

1138
01:09:00,461 --> 01:09:03,263
Thomas, why aren't you talking to anyone?

1139
01:09:04,731 --> 01:09:07,601
Well, why don't you tell them what happened?

1140
01:09:07,734 --> 01:09:11,839
[Thomas banging on table]

1141
01:09:13,974 --> 01:09:15,142
Okay.

1142
01:09:15,909 --> 01:09:17,845
If you would tell them what happened--

1143
01:09:19,246 --> 01:09:20,280
Tell--

1144
01:09:21,215 --> 01:09:24,251
[tense music]

1145
01:09:35,229 --> 01:09:36,463
[Crane] Oh, Ms. Collier.

1146
01:09:36,797 --> 01:09:38,866
Now what brings you down to the station here?

1147
01:09:40,634 --> 01:09:42,302
I came to see my client.

1148
01:09:42,436 --> 01:09:43,470
Wait, wait a second.

1149
01:09:43,804 --> 01:09:45,839
You tell me you're representing that man?

1150
01:09:46,540 --> 01:09:47,674
Yes, I am.

1151
01:09:54,815 --> 01:09:56,416
[Wallis sobbing]

1152
01:10:03,991 --> 01:10:06,326
[Clara] I need to talk to you.

1153
01:10:06,460 --> 01:10:07,761
We just got the call.

1154
01:10:09,530 --> 01:10:13,000
I don't understand how you can do this to me, Clara.

1155
01:10:13,133 --> 01:10:14,168
Let me explain.

1156
01:10:14,301 --> 01:10:16,069
No, I don't want an explanation.

1157
01:10:16,203 --> 01:10:18,405
Nothing you're gonna say could make me understand.

1158
01:10:19,173 --> 01:10:21,675
- We don't know what happened. - What happened?

1159
01:10:22,809 --> 01:10:23,977
What happened?

1160
01:10:25,112 --> 01:10:26,747
Jamie went into the woods to visit that man

1161
01:10:26,880 --> 01:10:28,315
and now he's not waking up.

1162
01:10:29,583 --> 01:10:30,851
He's not waking up.

1163
01:10:31,552 --> 01:10:33,754
[Wallis crying]

1164
01:10:36,990 --> 01:10:38,525
[Wallis] Oh God.

1165
01:10:39,960 --> 01:10:41,695
[breathing heavily]

1166
01:10:43,130 --> 01:10:44,398
Oh God.

1167
01:10:44,531 --> 01:10:45,966
You just--

1168
01:10:46,366 --> 01:10:47,401
Get out.

1169
01:10:50,904 --> 01:10:52,039
Just get out!

1170
01:10:58,011 --> 01:10:59,279
[Wallis crying]

1171
01:10:59,913 --> 01:11:01,748
[Wallis] Get out of my house!

1172
01:11:05,552 --> 01:11:09,456
[solemn music]

1173
01:11:20,434 --> 01:11:22,970
[dog barking]

1174
01:11:39,620 --> 01:11:41,388
[dog barking]

1175
01:12:03,277 --> 01:12:04,711
[bell ringing]

1176
01:12:04,845 --> 01:12:06,246
- [man] Can I help you? - Yes.

1177
01:12:06,380 --> 01:12:08,282
I was hoping to find Ray Little.

1178
01:12:08,682 --> 01:12:11,618
He worked here as a pharmacist in '94.

1179
01:12:11,752 --> 01:12:14,121
Yeah, he was. But he moved back up north.

1180
01:12:14,321 --> 01:12:15,355
Maybe I can help you.

1181
01:12:15,822 --> 01:12:18,425
Well, I'm looking for information about a robbery

1182
01:12:18,558 --> 01:12:20,060
that took place here.

1183
01:12:20,227 --> 01:12:22,029
A man named Thomas Moore was involved.

1184
01:12:22,796 --> 01:12:24,998
I think I'm the one you should talk to.

1185
01:12:30,771 --> 01:12:34,908
Please, Mister Wishing Tree, make my friend Jamie wake up.

1186
01:12:38,512 --> 01:12:41,548
[eerie music]

1187
01:12:47,721 --> 01:12:49,856
[tense music]

1188
01:13:15,148 --> 01:13:18,518
[Wallis singing indistinctly]

1189
01:13:41,641 --> 01:13:44,244
[bell tolling]

1190
01:13:50,016 --> 01:13:51,385
[officer] You got five minutes.

1191
01:13:52,552 --> 01:13:53,854
[door shuts]

1192
01:13:54,755 --> 01:13:55,889
Hello, Thomas.

1193
01:14:02,195 --> 01:14:03,296
Are you okay?

1194
01:14:05,399 --> 01:14:06,700
It's all right.

1195
01:14:07,401 --> 01:14:11,004
I found out what happened at the pharmacy.

1196
01:14:13,407 --> 01:14:15,442
I understand what you're going through,

1197
01:14:15,976 --> 01:14:19,579
and I promise you, I'll get you out of here,

1198
01:14:21,715 --> 01:14:25,051
but you have to help me.

1199
01:14:25,619 --> 01:14:29,790
I need you to tell me exactly what happened.

1200
01:14:33,226 --> 01:14:35,962
[tense music]

1201
01:14:40,967 --> 01:14:42,002
Oh.

1202
01:14:45,939 --> 01:14:46,973
It's okay.

1203
01:14:47,107 --> 01:14:48,675
[breathing rapidly]

1204
01:14:50,710 --> 01:14:51,745
It's okay.

1205
01:15:01,455 --> 01:15:04,624
[birds singing]

1206
01:15:04,758 --> 01:15:05,792
[Wallis] Will?

1207
01:15:32,452 --> 01:15:35,322
[indistinct chattering]

1208
01:15:39,159 --> 01:15:40,327
[gavel banging]

1209
01:15:41,828 --> 01:15:45,832
[judge] Mr. Moore, you are charged with kidnapping,

1210
01:15:46,366 --> 01:15:48,535
which is a felony in the state of Georgia.

1211
01:15:49,369 --> 01:15:51,805
The purpose of this hearing is not to determine

1212
01:15:51,938 --> 01:15:54,841
whether you are guilty or not guilty of these charges.

1213
01:15:54,975 --> 01:15:58,678
It is simply to determine whether there is probable cause

1214
01:15:58,812 --> 01:16:02,048
to bind this case over to the district attorney's office

1215
01:16:02,182 --> 01:16:03,683
for further investigation.

1216
01:16:04,050 --> 01:16:06,353
If I find there is no probable cause,

1217
01:16:06,486 --> 01:16:08,121
you will be released today.

1218
01:16:09,723 --> 01:16:11,057
Do you have any questions

1219
01:16:11,191 --> 01:16:13,193
about what I have explained to you?

1220
01:16:13,660 --> 01:16:15,428
No, Your Honor, we're ready to proceed.

1221
01:16:16,496 --> 01:16:19,099
Officer Daniels, would you tell us what happened

1222
01:16:19,232 --> 01:16:21,468
after you placed the victim in your car?

1223
01:16:22,269 --> 01:16:25,405
Well, when I turned back towards the suspect, he was gone.

1224
01:16:26,172 --> 01:16:27,641
You mean he ran away?

1225
01:16:28,141 --> 01:16:29,643
[Daniels] I didn't see him.

1226
01:16:29,910 --> 01:16:31,278
Well yeah, I suppose he did.

1227
01:16:31,411 --> 01:16:32,779
[Clara] Officer Daniels,

1228
01:16:33,346 --> 01:16:35,448
why was your gun drawn when you stepped from the car?

1229
01:16:35,916 --> 01:16:38,618
[Daniels] There was an APB out on a possible kidnapping.

1230
01:16:39,052 --> 01:16:41,121
I assumed the suspect was dangerous.

1231
01:16:42,088 --> 01:16:43,590
He didn't answer my questions.

1232
01:16:43,723 --> 01:16:45,425
[Clara] Do you think there's any possibility

1233
01:16:45,559 --> 01:16:48,228
that my client could have feared for his life?

1234
01:16:49,529 --> 01:16:51,431
I'm a police officer, counselor.

1235
01:16:51,765 --> 01:16:53,266
And what, your bullets don't hurt?

1236
01:16:53,867 --> 01:16:55,068
Ms. Collier.

1237
01:16:55,835 --> 01:16:57,337
No further questions, Your Honor.

1238
01:17:00,740 --> 01:17:04,611
[Clara] Mr. Davies, would you describe him as a violent man?

1239
01:17:04,744 --> 01:17:07,581
[Davies] Oh no, quite the opposite in fact.

1240
01:17:07,948 --> 01:17:09,249
[Clara] Did he ever talk to you?

1241
01:17:09,549 --> 01:17:10,584
[Davies] No, ma'am.

1242
01:17:11,017 --> 01:17:13,053
Thomas was born without vocal chords.

1243
01:17:13,853 --> 01:17:15,989
But you are the head pharmacist

1244
01:17:16,122 --> 01:17:18,491
at the very store where Thomas

1245
01:17:18,625 --> 01:17:20,894
supposedly committed a violent robbery.

1246
01:17:21,595 --> 01:17:23,530
Yes, but that's not really what happened.

1247
01:17:23,663 --> 01:17:24,898
Oh?

1248
01:17:25,065 --> 01:17:27,968
Well, would you tell us all what really did happen?

1249
01:17:28,101 --> 01:17:29,369
[Davies] Yes.

1250
01:17:29,502 --> 01:17:33,473
Thomas's mother was diagnosed with bone cancer in 1987.

1251
01:17:34,240 --> 01:17:36,476
Within a few months, the illness had taken

1252
01:17:36,943 --> 01:17:38,845
just about every penny they had.

1253
01:17:38,979 --> 01:17:41,948
She was in so much pain, Thomas just couldn't bear it.

1254
01:17:42,082 --> 01:17:44,718
He came to the pharmacy to get something to help her.

1255
01:17:44,884 --> 01:17:47,020
Now, if I'd been there, I would just have given it to him.

1256
01:17:47,153 --> 01:17:48,521
I knew he didn't have any money.

1257
01:17:49,055 --> 01:17:51,191
But I'd just hired this new fella, Ray,

1258
01:17:51,324 --> 01:17:52,626
and he didn't understand.

1259
01:17:53,593 --> 01:17:55,962
When he wouldn't give Thomas the medication,

1260
01:17:56,463 --> 01:17:57,697
he grabbed for it

1261
01:17:58,298 --> 01:18:00,634
and accidentally, he broke Ray's hand.

1262
01:18:01,935 --> 01:18:03,837
But you pressed charges?

1263
01:18:03,970 --> 01:18:06,139
[Davies] No, I didn't, I had the robbery charge dropped,

1264
01:18:06,840 --> 01:18:09,242
but that fella, Ray, went ahead with the assault charge

1265
01:18:09,376 --> 01:18:11,511
on account of his hand being broke.

1266
01:18:12,379 --> 01:18:14,581
So, Thomas went to jail?

1267
01:18:14,714 --> 01:18:16,049
[Davies] Yes, he did.

1268
01:18:17,183 --> 01:18:18,551
And that's when it happened.

1269
01:18:19,119 --> 01:18:20,654
[Clara] What happened?

1270
01:18:20,787 --> 01:18:22,589
[Davies] His mother passed away.

1271
01:18:22,722 --> 01:18:24,557
I know that was hard on Thomas,

1272
01:18:25,158 --> 01:18:26,860
not being there when she died.

1273
01:18:26,993 --> 01:18:29,863
After he got out, he moved to the woods.

1274
01:18:30,296 --> 01:18:32,999
Pretty much stopped coming around.

1275
01:18:33,133 --> 01:18:36,536
To tell you the truth, I can't say I blame him.

1276
01:18:36,670 --> 01:18:38,438
[Clara] Detective Crane,

1277
01:18:38,571 --> 01:18:41,207
did you ever find any evidence that a crime

1278
01:18:41,341 --> 01:18:42,842
was committed by my client?

1279
01:18:43,576 --> 01:18:45,412
[Crane] Well, I find it hard to believe

1280
01:18:45,545 --> 01:18:48,415
that Jamie Caldwell beat up on himself, counselor.

1281
01:18:49,282 --> 01:18:52,352
Are you aware that my client was found carrying

1282
01:18:52,485 --> 01:18:55,155
Jamie Caldwell less than four tenths of a mile

1283
01:18:55,288 --> 01:18:57,223
from the Savannah General Hospital?

1284
01:18:57,857 --> 01:18:59,426
[clears throat] No, I wasn't.

1285
01:18:59,726 --> 01:19:02,529
Did it ever occur to you that he might be trying

1286
01:19:02,662 --> 01:19:04,197
to help Jamie Caldwell?

1287
01:19:04,998 --> 01:19:06,366
Well, I find that hard to believe.

1288
01:19:07,067 --> 01:19:08,101
Why is that?

1289
01:19:08,968 --> 01:19:11,638
Well, one thing experience has taught me is that,

1290
01:19:12,038 --> 01:19:14,741
innocent people don't run from the law.

1291
01:19:16,710 --> 01:19:18,745
[phone ringing]

1292
01:19:20,246 --> 01:19:21,881
You need to understand something.

1293
01:19:22,615 --> 01:19:24,884
If the judge thinks that there's even the slightest

1294
01:19:25,018 --> 01:19:27,253
possibility that a crime was committed,

1295
01:19:27,387 --> 01:19:29,222
you will be bound over for trial.

1296
01:19:29,355 --> 01:19:31,825
And if that happens, you will remain in jail

1297
01:19:31,958 --> 01:19:33,560
until that trial date.

1298
01:19:34,561 --> 01:19:36,896
Thomas, you can't do this to me.

1299
01:19:37,030 --> 01:19:38,498
I am doing everything I can to help you,

1300
01:19:38,631 --> 01:19:40,100
but you have to help me.

1301
01:19:41,768 --> 01:19:44,637
Listen, I don't know what went on out in those woods,

1302
01:19:44,771 --> 01:19:47,073
but I know that whatever it was, it was not your fault.

1303
01:19:47,207 --> 01:19:48,842
I know that, but they don't.

1304
01:19:48,975 --> 01:19:50,844
Only you can tell them that!

1305
01:19:55,648 --> 01:19:58,685
Your Honor, the defense calls Thomas Moore.

1306
01:20:20,540 --> 01:20:23,977
Mr. Moore, please place your right hand on the Bible.

1307
01:20:25,578 --> 01:20:26,780
Raise your left hand.

1308
01:20:27,981 --> 01:20:29,816
Do you swear to tell the truth,

1309
01:20:29,949 --> 01:20:32,252
the whole truth and nothing but the truth?

1310
01:20:33,653 --> 01:20:34,687
You may sit down.

1311
01:20:52,138 --> 01:20:55,642
Mr. Moore, I only have a few questions.

1312
01:20:58,244 --> 01:20:59,813
Are you acquainted with a young boy

1313
01:20:59,946 --> 01:21:02,048
by the name of Jamie Caldwell?

1314
01:21:11,624 --> 01:21:12,992
Thomas, look at me.

1315
01:21:16,896 --> 01:21:19,332
Are you acquainted with Jamie Caldwell?

1316
01:21:21,467 --> 01:21:22,502
[interpreter] Yes.

1317
01:21:23,803 --> 01:21:26,172
How would you describe your relationship?

1318
01:21:28,041 --> 01:21:29,709
He's my friend.

1319
01:21:29,843 --> 01:21:32,512
So, you care very deeply for him, don't you?

1320
01:21:34,747 --> 01:21:35,782
[interpreter] Yes.

1321
01:21:36,015 --> 01:21:37,350
Tell me, Mr. Moore.

1322
01:21:37,483 --> 01:21:40,119
Were you invited on August fourth to a party at the home

1323
01:21:40,286 --> 01:21:41,521
of the Albert Brooks's?

1324
01:21:42,822 --> 01:21:43,823
Yes.

1325
01:21:44,524 --> 01:21:46,125
And did you go to that party?

1326
01:21:48,394 --> 01:21:49,662
No.

1327
01:21:49,929 --> 01:21:50,964
[Clara] Why not?

1328
01:21:52,732 --> 01:21:56,069
- [interpreter] I was afraid. - You were afraid?

1329
01:21:56,302 --> 01:21:59,105
But why were you afraid to go to a party?

1330
01:22:00,673 --> 01:22:01,708
[interpreter] Look at me.

1331
01:22:03,409 --> 01:22:06,279
Look at how everyone looks at me.

1332
01:22:07,113 --> 01:22:09,716
I was afraid of being judged.

1333
01:22:12,685 --> 01:22:15,555
They don't understand me.

1334
01:22:15,688 --> 01:22:18,625
It hurts too much.

1335
01:22:21,027 --> 01:22:22,929
Does that make you angry, Thomas?

1336
01:22:24,530 --> 01:22:28,268
[interpreter] No, makes me very sad.

1337
01:22:30,136 --> 01:22:33,306
Thomas, did you know that your friend,

1338
01:22:33,439 --> 01:22:36,776
Jamie Caldwell, ran into the woods to look for you,

1339
01:22:36,910 --> 01:22:39,412
because he wanted you to come to that party?

1340
01:22:39,779 --> 01:22:43,449
[interpreter] No, not until I heard him calling me.

1341
01:22:44,284 --> 01:22:46,185
[dramatic music]

1342
01:22:46,319 --> 01:22:48,121
Magic Man!

1343
01:22:50,623 --> 01:22:53,259
- [thunder cracking] - [Jamie] Magic Man!

1344
01:22:55,995 --> 01:22:57,430
Magic Man!

1345
01:22:58,064 --> 01:22:59,666
[thunder cracking]

1346
01:22:59,899 --> 01:23:01,367
[Jamie screaming]

1347
01:23:04,070 --> 01:23:06,839
[music continues]

1348
01:23:16,349 --> 01:23:19,118
[exhaling dramatically]

1349
01:23:28,761 --> 01:23:31,130
- [tires screech] - [siren wails]

1350
01:23:32,665 --> 01:23:34,200
[Daniels] Stop right where you are.

1351
01:23:35,568 --> 01:23:37,704
Just put the boy on the ground, right now.

1352
01:23:38,471 --> 01:23:40,239
Put the boy on the ground!

1353
01:23:40,673 --> 01:23:41,708
Do it!

1354
01:23:47,914 --> 01:23:52,018
I was trying, trying to help him,

1355
01:23:53,753 --> 01:23:59,025
but I failed, I failed again.

1356
01:24:02,462 --> 01:24:04,330
I'm so sorry.

1357
01:24:05,398 --> 01:24:11,404
More sorry than you will ever know.

1358
01:24:16,609 --> 01:24:18,344
You didn't fail, Thomas.

1359
01:24:21,514 --> 01:24:22,715
We failed you.

1360
01:24:31,557 --> 01:24:34,927
You see, a lot of times,

1361
01:24:35,561 --> 01:24:38,664
we don't understand people who are unlike us.

1362
01:24:40,666 --> 01:24:43,436
And rather than trying to understand,

1363
01:24:43,569 --> 01:24:44,937
we simply reject them.

1364
01:24:46,039 --> 01:24:48,207
I don't know what we are so afraid of.

1365
01:24:48,341 --> 01:24:51,377
Perhaps we fear that through association,

1366
01:24:51,511 --> 01:24:53,179
we too might be judged.

1367
01:24:56,616 --> 01:24:59,085
We hear you, Thomas.

1368
01:24:59,218 --> 01:25:00,653
You didn't fail your mother,

1369
01:25:02,221 --> 01:25:05,958
and you didn't fail your friend, Jamie Caldwell.

1370
01:25:10,763 --> 01:25:12,965
Looking at the facts of this case,

1371
01:25:14,167 --> 01:25:17,737
I have come to the conclusion that we should not be here,

1372
01:25:17,870 --> 01:25:19,605
judging Thomas Moore.

1373
01:25:21,607 --> 01:25:23,309
We should be apologizing.

1374
01:25:25,478 --> 01:25:27,180
I find no probable cause.

1375
01:25:27,313 --> 01:25:28,881
- [gavel bangs] - Case dismissed.

1376
01:25:31,217 --> 01:25:32,251
Yeah.

1377
01:25:35,288 --> 01:25:38,157
[gentle music]

1378
01:25:39,459 --> 01:25:40,493
Good job.

1379
01:25:50,036 --> 01:25:52,271
It's Jamie, he wants to see Jamie.

1380
01:25:55,341 --> 01:25:56,809
- Come. - I can't thank you enough

1381
01:25:56,943 --> 01:25:57,977
for coming.

1382
01:25:58,111 --> 01:26:00,847
[indistinct chattering]

1383
01:26:02,949 --> 01:26:04,383
[gentle piano music]

1384
01:26:04,517 --> 01:26:08,654
[woman speaking indistinctly over PA]

1385
01:26:11,424 --> 01:26:12,925
Magic Man!

1386
01:26:25,171 --> 01:26:28,307
[solemn music]

1387
01:27:10,850 --> 01:27:13,686
[music continues]

1388
01:27:27,133 --> 01:27:28,701
[Professor] Now magic can sometimes

1389
01:27:28,834 --> 01:27:30,269
take a little while to work.

1390
01:27:31,737 --> 01:27:34,774
In this case, it was about two hours

1391
01:27:34,907 --> 01:27:39,912
after Magic Man left that Jamie finally opened his eyes.

1392
01:27:41,180 --> 01:27:43,983
I think it's because I found the wishing tree.

1393
01:27:44,150 --> 01:27:45,251
Well, if you found it,

1394
01:27:45,384 --> 01:27:47,753
then how come you don't show it to us?

1395
01:27:48,321 --> 01:27:50,223
Because I forgot to mark it.

1396
01:27:50,356 --> 01:27:52,258
[Professor chuckles]

1397
01:27:52,758 --> 01:27:54,260
[Clara laughs]

1398
01:28:04,036 --> 01:28:06,205
I thought you said we weren't going far.

1399
01:28:06,339 --> 01:28:08,808
[gentle music]

1400
01:28:10,443 --> 01:28:11,611
We're here.

1401
01:28:14,380 --> 01:28:15,414
The tree?

1402
01:28:16,215 --> 01:28:18,251
Yeah, it is, it's very big.

1403
01:28:18,884 --> 01:28:21,220
It must be over several hundred years old.

1404
01:28:26,993 --> 01:28:29,629
[music continues]

1405
01:28:36,769 --> 01:28:38,271
What are you doing?

1406
01:28:40,106 --> 01:28:42,608
[mysterious music]

1407
01:28:49,382 --> 01:28:50,483
What is that?

1408
01:28:51,951 --> 01:28:53,119
A bullet?

1409
01:28:54,920 --> 01:28:57,890
No. Why would anybody go shoot up a tree?

1410
01:29:06,932 --> 01:29:08,067
You think?

1411
01:29:13,472 --> 01:29:15,041
The wishing tree.

1412
01:29:17,843 --> 01:29:20,379
[music continues]

1413
01:29:32,825 --> 01:29:34,760
What, you want me to make a wish?

1414
01:29:39,465 --> 01:29:43,002
[gentle music]

1415
01:30:06,926 --> 01:30:08,260
- [man] Clara? - Mm?

1416
01:30:08,761 --> 01:30:10,096
This just arrived for you.

1417
01:30:11,997 --> 01:30:13,032
What is it?

1418
01:30:13,399 --> 01:30:14,967
There's no return address.

1419
01:30:17,903 --> 01:30:19,038
- Wait. - What?

1420
01:30:19,372 --> 01:30:20,406
What if it's a bomb?

1421
01:30:20,539 --> 01:30:21,874
Oh, Kevin, please.

1422
01:30:22,041 --> 01:30:23,509
Who's gonna send me a bomb?

1423
01:30:23,642 --> 01:30:25,044
Well, Clara, you're a lawyer.

1424
01:30:25,177 --> 01:30:26,212
You want a list?

1425
01:30:27,747 --> 01:30:30,416
Oh, oh!

1426
01:30:30,883 --> 01:30:31,917
Who is that?

1427
01:30:33,285 --> 01:30:34,320
That's my mother.

1428
01:30:36,255 --> 01:30:37,757
He knew my mother.

1429
01:30:38,958 --> 01:30:41,761
[gentle music]

1430
01:30:53,706 --> 01:30:57,109
[Clara] As I looked at that beautiful carving,

1431
01:30:57,243 --> 01:31:01,247
I realized I finally understood,

1432
01:31:03,916 --> 01:31:07,286
that Thomas in many ways was like the man my mother

1433
01:31:07,420 --> 01:31:11,157
used to talk about, the one who lived out in the woods.

1434
01:31:11,290 --> 01:31:16,829
You see, when I got lost, he brought me back home.

1435
01:31:18,564 --> 01:31:22,568
And that is where this story ends.

1436
01:31:24,336 --> 01:31:26,639
[Alexa] Wait a second. What you wish for at the tree?

1437
01:31:26,772 --> 01:31:27,807
[child] Yeah.

1438
01:31:28,407 --> 01:31:30,142
Oh, what do you think I wished for?

1439
01:31:30,276 --> 01:31:31,343
[Alexa] I don't know.

1440
01:31:31,710 --> 01:31:32,978
What did you wish for?

1441
01:31:33,779 --> 01:31:35,347
What do you think I wished for?

1442
01:31:37,349 --> 01:31:39,785
You wished you could go back in the forest?

1443
01:31:42,488 --> 01:31:46,926
[Jamie] I think you wished that you could be magic,

1444
01:31:47,259 --> 01:31:49,195
like Magic Man.

1445
01:31:49,328 --> 01:31:50,830
Jamie, you wouldn't need magic

1446
01:31:50,963 --> 01:31:52,765
if you're friends with Magic Man.

1447
01:31:53,165 --> 01:31:55,134
- [child] That's right. - I think I'd wish

1448
01:31:55,267 --> 01:31:56,302
I could fly.

1449
01:31:56,569 --> 01:31:58,771
[child] Yeah, so would I.

1450
01:31:59,438 --> 01:32:00,706
Know what I'd wish for?

1451
01:32:04,777 --> 01:32:06,545
I'd wish your mother could see you now.

1452
01:32:12,685 --> 01:32:15,187
Well, I'm not gonna tell you what I wished for,

1453
01:32:16,522 --> 01:32:17,957
but it did come true.

1454
01:32:19,658 --> 01:32:21,861
[gentle music]

1455
01:32:22,995 --> 01:32:26,065
And with or without the wishing tree,

1456
01:32:27,233 --> 01:32:30,202
if you believe, yours will too.

1457
01:32:35,875 --> 01:32:37,443
Cherish it.

1458
01:32:47,853 --> 01:32:51,290
[bright music]

